22. edicta Iulia. We must no more look for a technical mean- ing in ‘ edicta,‘ than for exact historical facts to correspond with the general statement. ‘Edictum,’ though limited very much in use to the praetor‘s edicts, was a general term for any command issued by a magistrate. The form of the phrase is intended to recall ‘leges Iuliae,’ the name which covered the domestic legisla- tion of Augustus as well as Julius. The substance, so far as it had any which can be realized, would be terms of peace, which Augustus has imposed on the various nations.
